    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-05-20T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-05-20T16:00:00-05:00" n="147"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d147">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7908: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-20T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 20, 1936—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>34. Your 143, May 18, noon.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Referring to paragraph 1 of your telegram, the Under Secretary at the
                        press conference May 16 in response to a question whether this Government
                        had taken any steps to determine whether Japan’s action in strengthening its
                        garrison in North China violated the Boxer Protocol<note n="89"
                            xml:id="d147fn89">Signed at Peking, September 7, 1901, <ref
                                target="frus1901China#pg_312">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1901, Appendix (Affairs in
                                China), p. 312</ref>.</note> replied that in his opinion the
                        Secretary’s public statement made on December 5, 1935, covers the
                        situation.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>A translation of the note referred to in paragraph 4 of your telegram does
                        not appear to have been published in the United States. It is suggested that
                        you send by naval radio a summary of the note and forward the text by mail.
                        However, should you consider that the complete text would be of interest to
                        the Department at this time, please send it by naval radio.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
